  title: "Duty of Candour Policy and Procedure",
  policyId: "GOV-001",
  version: "2.0",
  reviewedBy: "Registered Manager / Nominated Individual",
  purpose: "This policy delivers the statutory duty of candour: when care goes wrong and a person is harmed, the service tells them promptly, honestly and in person, apologises, explains what is known and what will be done, and follows it all up in writing. It exists because harmed people are owed the truth as a matter of decency before law, because openness is the fastest route to learning, and because the cover-up — not the original error — is what destroys services. Candour done well is painful for an afternoon; candour done badly is fatal to trust forever.",
  scope: "Applies to every notifiable safety incident involving a person using the service, to all staff (who trigger the duty by honest incident reporting), and to the Registered Manager and senior team who carry the formal steps. It sits alongside — never instead of — the professional duty of candour that registered clinicians owe individually, and it operates in parallel with incident, safeguarding, complaints and CQC-notification machinery (gov-005), none of which waits for any other.",
