      heading: "When something goes wrong",
      body: "Immediate response follows the person's needs and the delegation's escalation plan: make safe, call the escalation contact or emergency services by the stop-and-call criteria, and inform the family per the care plan. Then the machinery engages: incident report the same shift; the delegating professional informed always — including for near-misses, because the professional cannot review what they never hear about; duty of candour (gov-001) where harm occurred; and gov-005 notification where the threshold is met.\n\nThe review that follows asks the system questions before the person questions, in this order: was the delegation itself sound; was the training and assessment adequate; had anything changed that should have paused it; was the worker supported with the currency and staffing to perform it well — and only then, was the performance at fault. A worker who performed as trained, within a delegation that turned out to be flawed, is a second victim, not a culprit, and the support offered says so. Learning goes to the register, the training, and — where the pattern crosses people — to gov-002's governance cycle."
