      body: "Flexibility across weeks is the plan keeping pace with the person. Triggers for same-week plan updates rather than waiting for the scheduled review: a new expressed preference that recurs, recovery or deterioration changing what the person can and wants to do, a change in family or community rhythm (a new club, a lost lift, a bereavement), and any accumulation of in-the-moment flexes pointing the same direction — five consecutive requests for a later start is not five anomalies; it is a preference the plan has not caught up with, and the keyworker owns spotting exactly this pattern before the review cycle would.\n\nIn domiciliary care, schedule changes follow the person's life: a standing visit moved for a hospital appointment is rebooked around the appointment, not cancelled into it; a person whose needs have grown gets the visit length reviewed with commissioners promptly, with the interim gap named as a risk (dc-005) rather than absorbed silently by rushed care. Supported living applies the same rule to support hours: the person's week drives the deployment, and a person whose recorded week has not changed in a year is asked whether that is contentment or resignation — the two look identical in a schedule and nothing alike in a life."
